            "answer_text": "The short answer is that edges got damaged a lot, had to be resharpened pretty consistently, and had to be reground periodically. Gun barrels get fouled when you use a gun. Sword edges get damaged when you use a sword. It's the nature of the tool. The long answer \u2026 What damaged an edge when fighting? Sword edges get damaged pretty much every time they hit something - but some things damage edges more than others. Imagine you own a nice sharp chef\u2019s knife. You slice through a thick ham with it, bone and all, against a proper cutting board. You clean your knife carefully and store it properly. Has your knife\u2019s edge been damaged? Well, of course it has - just not very much. You will probably notice no decrease in performance the next time you cut a ham. A thousand hams later, you will definitely notice that your knife is not as sharp as it used to be. Now imagine taking that knife and running it through a dishwasher with a bunch of other knives, clattering together in a single utensil basket. This will obviously also dull your knife, much more quickly than simply cutting through meat. Same if you cut through a ham against a stainless steel cutting surface. There are basically two categories of objects sword edges encounter in fighting: things they can cut through, and things they can't. Things they can cut through include flesh, bone, textiles, and at the outside cases, soft metal like brass. Things they can't include hard metal like steel and most wooden objects they're likely to encounter in a fight. Hitting any of these objects will adversely affect a sword edge, but hitting the second category will cause edge damage much, much faster (like, orders of magnitude faster). How do edges get damaged in a fight? There are basically two ways for an edge to get damaged in a fight. The first is for the edge to become bent. This is a cross-section of what that looks like:  But if you look at the edge as a whole, it might look like this:  In this case, no regrinding is necessary: the metal of the edge is still there, you just need to coax it back into line with the rest of the edge using a stone or steel tool. This happens in kitchens around the world every day. If your weapon is well made, then this is the most common type of \u201cdamage\u201d it will suffer, even in aggressive fighting. Just straighten the edge, repolish it, and you're good to go. If your sword is less well made, or you simply get unlucky, then you might actually notch your edge. This means that there is actual metal missing from the edge, like the left hand image here:  There's no way to fix this other than to grind away the whole edge below the level of the notch, as in the right-hand image. Obviously this can only happen to a weapon so many times before you have ground it away to nothing. Fortunately, as I said, it isn't common with well made swords. You also may not need to grind out the notch. A notched blade will still cut, it just isn't as good at it (just as you can still hit a target with a fouled gun barrel). If the notch is small, and/or in a part of the blade that isn't used for offensive action much, you might decide to just leave it there. How often do you need to maintain an edge? So, how often would a weapon need to be reground and sharpened over its lifetime? Those are two different things. An edge might not need to be reground ever, since that's only necessary for notching. As for sharpening, though \u2026 you should expect to have to straighten an edge every time you fight. If you were parried even once, or struck wood or metal even once, odds are very good that you'll have a bent edge somewhere on your blade that needs straightening. You might even have a bent edge from a failed cut (e.g., your edge got stuck in somebody\u2019s bone), and possibly even from successful cuts (the thousand hams problem). Straightening your edge is normal post-fight maintenance, same as re-oiling your blade. If you straightened your edge, you really ought to repolish it (frankly, in my opinion, you ought to touch up your polish even after test cutting soft materials, though that's a bit outside the scope of the question). So you might never need to regrind your blade, although the odds are good you\u2019ll have to do it several times over its life. You\u2019ll need to sharpen your blade constantly, though. ",
