            "answer_text": "Historical swordsman knew their trade and refrained from striking swords edge on edge. The weaker sword would break, leaving it's owner with a useless stump and his opponent with the rest of the sword stuck in body parts. Not good for either. A good quality sword was also very expensive (about one years\u2019 income of the average person), so you could not afford to just go and buy a new one. Also, straight edged swords as used by knights were mainly used to break bones behind armor and thus not really sharpened, just at the tip to allow the occasional poke through the joints in the armor. Modern show fighting is for show, with the purpose to entertain an audience with a prolonged fight and lots of sparks. Show fighting swords have a 2mm \u201cedge\u201d that is not hardened and can be hammered flat without risking breakage. ",
